title: For Sale/Trade:  BRITISH ENFIELD #4 MK 1
postcontent:
I have a British Enfield #4 MK 1 (.303 British of course) that has had the stock cut down and re-finished. Here is a little info on the Enfield #4 for reference:

The Rifle, No. 4 Mk I was first issued in 1939 but not officially adopted until 1941.[30] The No. 4 action was similar to the Mk VI,[31] but lighter, stronger, and most importantly, easier to mass produce.[31] Unlike the SMLE, the No 4 Lee-Enfield barrel protruded from the end of the forestock. The No. 4 rifle was considerably heavier than the No. 1 Mk. III, largely due to its heavier barrel,[31] and a new bayonet was designed to go with the rifle: a spike bayonet,[31] which was essentially a steel rod with a sharp point, and was nicknamed "pigsticker" by soldiers. Towards the end of the Second World War, a bladed bayonet was developed, originally intended for use with the Sten gun-but sharing the same mount as the No. 4's spike bayonet-and subsequently the No. 7 and No. 9 blade bayonets were issued for use with the No. 4 rifle as well.

Gun is in pretty good shape, I purchased it around 15 years ago and have owned it since. It has had 1 box of ammo down the tube from me and then sat in the safe. I will provide 1 box of Winchester 303 and another of brass with it for the asking price.

title: For Sale:  S&W M&P15 (ar15) + many extras and 1200+ rds!
postcontent:
Selling this combat worthy carbine, all the extras, and all the ammo for 1500.  It has about 300 rounds through it without any issues.  It's been well kept and properly cleaned.  Unlike lesser quality rifles, the Smith & Wesson M&P15 utilizes these important military specs:

4140 barrel steel, MPI/HPT tested barrel and bolt carrier (batch), shot peened/MPI/HPT bolt, properly staked gas key, chrome chamber and bore, 5.56 chamber, M4 feed ramps, F marked FSB, Parkerizing under FSB, Receiver ext. diamerter of 1.14", and a black extractor spring insert.  Several of these important standards are missing with armalite/sabre defence/cmmg/stag/bushmaster/rra/oly arms/dpms rifles.  Such standards are what matter in a battle rifle when you get between 1k and 15k rounds.namely in bolt longevity.


The prices I paid for everything over the last few months includes:
$1065 - S&W M&P15 with Magpul stock, magazine, mbus, moe handguard, moe grip (with batteries stored in it)..hard case included.
$10 - magpul moe trigger guard
$45 - three magpul pmags
$90 - primary arms micro RDS & riser (very sharp dot, bright in daytime, guaranteed)
$25 - rear receiver plate with two loops for sling hooks
$15 - three magpul polymer 5 slot rails for moe handguard
$30 - tapco universal 2pt sling
$30 - desert tactical 1pt bungee sling
$20 - tapco vertical forward grip (cut down to shorty length, has batteries in it)
$96 - ncstar 5mw green laser with normal cap or pressure switch (hasn't lost zero over a couple hundred rounds! And shows its beam at night over 2 miles..and 300 yards during noon day sun!)
$130 - olight m30 triton light;  700 lumen with high/med/low/12hz strobe and strobe button
$20 - bayo lug pic rail mount
$15 - 1" light mount
$450 - 1200+ rds 55gr ammo fmj & psp

title: For Sale:  PSL 54c/ROMAK III/Dragunov  7.62x54r
postcontent:
This is a Century imported Romanian made (Cugir factory) PSL 54c.  Also known as the ROMAK III...and also known as the Romanian Dragunov.  These rifles are actually based on the hard hitting and very accurate Romanian RPK machine gun and designed to be a designated marksman rifle.  Call it what you will, it's a hard hitting, dang good looking, and very cheap to shoot rifle that'll get you up to 1.5MOA if you do your part.

It shoots the 7.62x54r round which is easy to find in military surplus cirlces like AIM surplus, ammunition to go, and most of the popular gun/accessories sites online.  20 cents a round for mildly corrosive ammo (which is easy to clean, don't be fooled) and you have power that bests the .308 and rivals the 30-06.  

The POSP type optic has very good glass, an excellent combat reticle, fine adjustments, and it slides on and off the rifle base effortlessly but stays put under fire.

If you're reading this post you already know what this rifle is and you've long wanted one.  This has a total of 50 rounds through it and it's pretty much rid of it's cosmoline.  It comes with one 10 round mag and I have a full size aftermarket case to put it in for you.  The furniture is very attractive on this one and the fit is excellent.  Sometimes the raging monkeys at Century put these together poorly, but lately (and this is evidence of it), they've been doing a good job.

Contact me for questions or to buy!
